editorialSummary.text: Romantic, old-school piano lounge with a dress code, plus cocktails & fancy bites like caviar.

originalText.text: We had a fantastic time celebrating a birthday at the Nines. The atmosphere was sexy and moody with great lighting and music. The service was spectacular, greeted with a happy birthday, they accommodated us bringing a cake ($5 fee/person) they added candles, coordinated a round of cocktails paid by family member over the phone in advance! The martinis and manhattans were perfection and served with your own overflow pitcher on ice. The burger and steak were delicious and not too large. I would absolutely return, to make any night feel like a really special occasion.

originalText.text:
A classy old school establishment with live piano (no singing), speakeasy vibe, and great but pricey cocktails. The dress code is prescribed but not strictly enforced (a guy next to us wore shorts).
The bar area is small, around 10 seats. The crudites app is huge and comes with quite a heavy almond dip, I and my friend shared it and were very stuffed.

originalText.text: Real Tasty says Frank.  Our reviews had over 37 million views last year.  We do not get paid we just love to eat and have fun.  We really loved The Nines.  Get dressed up!!!!  Great food, great vibe, great music.  Had a blast there on a Thursday night from 8-10 pm.  Piano player from 6-9 then another one from 9-midnight.  Then stays open as a fun club until 2 am.  Club Acme is downstairs from 10 to 4 am.  You must dress up A LOT for both places.  Drinks are $20-$27 and food varies a lot.  We posted photos of all the menus with prices so you can see how much because they do not say online.  Loved the hamburger and loved the Gundi which is gnocchi made with ricotta cheese.  Desserts are super great and the smoked salmon app was HUGE.  $99 twice baked potato was worth every penny!!!  Great place we will be back to many times.  LOVED IT!!!!  Check out all of our reviews. If we do not like it we do no review it so all of the ones you see are places that are fantastic. Follow us if you like. We had over 36 million views so far this year and we thank you for that. We don't get paid, we just love to eat. Be sure to click on "RobH" at the top of this review to see all of them and to follow us if you like good food and FUN.  If we do a review it is because we love it.

originalText.text: Absolutely loved this place! It says ACME on the outside which is deceiving but in the best way. You walk in and once you cross into the main dining room you are transported. South a swanky, hip vibe! The potato with caviar was amazing, the burger was solid! Everything we had was on point. It is a locals gem so make sure you add this to your list!

originalText.text:
Me and my friends dined at The Nines in New York a few weeks ago and unfortunately, our experience was marred by the rude behaviour of the waiter. Here's a breakdown of my disappointing visit:

Our encounter with the waiter started on a sour note when we asked for recommendations on tequila within the $20 range. His dismissive response, stating, "you're not going to find that here," was not only inaccurate but also displayed a lack of willingness to assist. It left a negative impression right from the beginning.

To add to our dissatisfaction, our bill amounted to $134 after the conversion rate from Australian to US dollars. This, coupled with the mandatory tipping culture, significantly inflated the overall cost of our meal. The pricing seemed excessive, especially given the level of service we received.

Despite the below-minimum tip we left, which we believed was warranted due to the waiter's behaviour, he took it upon himself to chase us to the downstairs bar. His insistence that we "needed" to give at least a 20% tip was not only unprofessional but bordered on harassment. We firmly believe that his service did not merit even a dollar, let alone the demanded 20%.

In conclusion, the combination of the waiter's rude demeanour, the inflated bill, and the unwarranted pressure to tip left a lasting negative impression on our experience at The Nines. It's disheartening to encounter such behaviour in what is supposed to be an upscale dining establishment. We hope that management addresses these issues to ensure a more pleasant dining experience for future patrons.
